236:\begin{theorem}\leanok
238:  \label{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}
239:  \uses{def:JacobianWitness, def:genusZeroWitness, def:positiveGenusWitness}
241:  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.nonempty_jacobianWitness}
245:  % thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness), not the other way around. Listing
247:  % a 2-cycle in plastex's depgraph (def:Jacobian ↔ thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness)
259:  The proof is split into three classical constructions plus the genus-\(0\) sub-case absorbed into the same witness (the latter packaged as the explicit construction \cref{def:genusZeroWitness}, which routes through the characteristic-free keystone \cref{prop:rigidity_genus0_curve_to_AV} of \cref{chap:AbelianVarietyRigidity} --- rigidity proved over the algebraic closure \(\bar k = \mathrm{AlgebraicClosure}\,k\) --- and then \emph{descends} the resulting morphism equality from \(\bar k\) to the base field \(k\) along the faithfully-flat surjection \(\Spec \bar k \to \Spec k\)). Each route produces the same intrinsic scheme \(J\); only the universal morphism \(\iota_P \colon C \to J\) varies with the marked point \(P\). We outline each route and name the Mathlib infrastructure each one requires.
425:  When \(g(C) = 0\) the witness's underlying scheme is \(J = \Spec k\), and the universal property reduces to a rigidity statement.
428:    \item[\textbf{(C.2)}] \emph{Rigidity for morphisms from \(\mathbb P^1\) to an abelian variety.} We state the rigidity result over the algebraic closure \(\bar k\), since the protected signature of Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} does not assume \(C(k) \neq \emptyset\) and the genus-\(0\) identification \(C \cong \mathbb P^1\) is only available after passing to \(\bar k\) (Brauer--Severi conics over \(\mathbb Q\) are the standard counterexamples to a \(k\)-side identification without a rational point). The conclusion over \(k\) --- equality of the given morphism with the constant morphism as \(k\)-schemes --- then follows by \emph{descent}: a morphism equality that holds after base change to \(\bar k\) descends to \(k\) along the faithfully-flat surjection \(\Spec \bar k \to \Spec k\) (Sub-step~C.2.f).
449:      \item[\textbf{(C.2.f)}] \emph{Descent of morphism equality from \(\bar k\) to \(k\).} The rigidity conclusion of Sub-step~C.2.d is proved over the algebraic closure \(\bar k = \mathrm{AlgebraicClosure}\,k\), where the characteristic-free keystone \cref{prop:rigidity_genus0_curve_to_AV} (\cref{chap:AbelianVarietyRigidity}) carries the hypothesis \([\mathtt{IsAlgClosed}\ \bar k]\) and, being characteristic-free, no \([\mathtt{CharZero}]\). To obtain the corresponding equality of morphisms over the base field \(k\), we descend along the base change \(\Spec \bar k \to \Spec k\).
450:      Concretely, let \(f, c \colon C \to A\) be two \(k\)-morphisms (in the application \(f\) is the given map and \(c\) the constant map at \(\eta_A\)). Base-change along \(\Spec \bar k \to \Spec k\) produces \(f_{\bar k}, c_{\bar k} \colon C_{\bar k} \to A_{\bar k}\) together with the projections \(p \colon C_{\bar k} = C \times_k \bar k \to C\) and \(q \colon A_{\bar k} \to A\), fitting the base-change squares \(q \circ f_{\bar k} = f \circ p\) and \(q \circ c_{\bar k} = c \circ p\). Suppose \(f_{\bar k} = c_{\bar k}\) (this is what \cref{prop:rigidity_genus0_curve_to_AV} delivers over \(\bar k\)). Then \(f \circ p = q \circ f_{\bar k} = q \circ c_{\bar k} = c \circ p\), so \(f\) and \(c\) agree after pre-composition with \(p\).
451:      It remains to right-cancel \(p\). The morphism \(\Spec \bar k \to \Spec k\) is faithfully flat (a field extension is a faithfully flat ring map) and surjective; both properties are stable under base change, so the projection \(p \colon C_{\bar k} \to C\) is faithfully flat and surjective. By \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Flat.epi\_of\_flat\_of\_surjective}, \(p\) is therefore an epimorphism of schemes, and right-cancelling it in \(f \circ p = c \circ p\) gives \(f = c\) over \(k\). \emph{This closing epi-cancellation is the only genuinely \(\sim 2\)-line part.} The descent as a whole is \textbf{not} a \(\sim 2\)-line step but a multi-iteration base-change sub-build: neither this project nor Mathlib provides a base-change functor \(\mathrm{Over}\,(\Spec k) \to \mathrm{Over}\,(\Spec \bar k)\), so even producing \(f_{\bar k}, c_{\bar k}\) and the base-change squares \(q \circ f_{\bar k} = f \circ p\) above first requires (a) that functor; (b) transfer of every relevant instance along it (\(\mathtt{SmoothOfRelativeDimension}\,1\), \(\mathtt{IsProper}\), \(\mathtt{GeometricallyIrreducible}\), \(\mathtt{GrpObj}\)); (c) stability of \(\genus = 0\) under the base change \(\Spec \bar k \to \Spec k\) for a geometrically irreducible curve; and (d) the base-change-square commutativity identities. All four must be in place before the closing epi-cancellation applies; only that final cancellation is short, while the surrounding base-change infrastructure is the bulk of the cost.
452:      \item[\textbf{(C.2.g)}] \emph{Mathlib gap statement.} The keystone fact of Sub-step~C.2.d --- that every morphism from a smooth proper geometrically irreducible genus-\(0\) curve over an algebraically closed field \(\bar k\) to a positive-dimensional smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme over \(\bar k\) is constant --- is \emph{not} present in current Mathlib (snapshot \texttt{b80f227}) in any form usable here. The project records the committed, characteristic-free form as the named declaration \cref{prop:rigidity_genus0_curve_to_AV} of \cref{chap:AbelianVarietyRigidity} (carrying \([\mathtt{IsAlgClosed}\ \bar k]\) and \emph{no} \([\mathtt{CharZero}]\) hypothesis); the older over-\(\bar k\) declaration \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} of \cref{chap:RigidityKbar}, whose base field still carries both \([\mathtt{IsAlgClosed}\ \bar k]\) and \([\mathtt{CharZero}\ \bar k]\), is retained only as the fallback-(a) artifact. The \textbf{committed} proof route is route~(c) of C.2.d: the Milne \S I.3 rigidity chain (cube-free) (\cref{chap:AbelianVarietyRigidity}, headline \cref{prop:morphism_P1_to_AV_constant} feeding \cref{prop:rigidity_genus0_curve_to_AV}), which is characteristic-free and uses neither the theorem of the cube, nor Serre duality, nor the Picard engine. The differential decomposition into the shared cotangent-vanishing pile of \cref{sec:RigidityKbar_shared_pile} pieces (i)--(iii) --- (i) cotangent triviality of a group scheme over \(\bar k\) via the functorial shear iso; (ii) scheme-level \(\mathrm d f = 0 \Rightarrow\) \(f\) factors through \(\Spec \bar k\) via the \texttt{Differential.ContainConstants} typeclass plus the iter-125-refactored \texttt{Scheme.Over.ext\_of\_eqOnOpen}; (iii) characteristic-\(p\) handling via the intrinsic absolute Frobenius \(F_X\) --- is the \textbf{fallback} route~(a), off the critical path but retained in the tree (each piece an upstream Mathlib gap-fill in its own right; see \cref{chap:RigidityKbar}). When \(g = \dim A = 0\) the statement is vacuous and the declaration's conclusion is automatic. The reduction step C.2.b reuses the project's already-formalised Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} (after the iter-125 refactor, this is \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Over.ext\_of\_eqOnOpen}, stated at the scheme level: source reduced and geometrically irreducible, target separated); the promotion step C.2.e uses standard reduced-source / separated-target lemmas, partially in Mathlib. The descent step C.2.f --- from \(\bar k\) back to the base field \(k\) --- has a genuinely short \emph{final} move (the epi-cancellation via \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Flat.epi\_of\_flat\_of\_surjective}, already in Mathlib in \texttt{Mathlib.AlgebraicGeometry.Morphisms.Flat}), but the descent as a whole is \emph{not} a \(\sim 2\)-line step: it is a multi-iteration base-change sub-build, because neither this project nor Mathlib provides a base-change functor \(\mathrm{Over}\,(\Spec k) \to \mathrm{Over}\,(\Spec \bar k)\), and the instance transfer, genus-stability, and base-change-square identities (C.2.f items (a)--(d)) must all be built before the closing epi-cancellation applies.
454:    \item[\textbf{(C.3)}] \emph{The trivial witness.} Take \(J := \Spec k\), the terminal \(k\)-scheme. The group-object structure on \(\Spec k\) is trivial; it is smooth proper geometrically irreducible of relative dimension \(0 = g(C)\). The unique morphism \(\iota_P \colon C \to \Spec k\) sends \(P\) to the (unique) point. By Sub-step C.2 every \(f \colon C \to A\) with \(f(P) = \eta_A\) is constant at \(\eta_A\), hence factors uniquely through the unique morphism \(g \colon \Spec k \to A\) sending the point to \(\eta_A\); uniqueness of \(g\) follows because \(\Spec k \to A\) is determined by its value on the unique \(k\)-rational point of \(\Spec k\).
465:    \item[\textbf{(\(\alpha\))}] \emph{Hilbert / Quot scheme infrastructure plus FGA representability (COMMITTED M3 infrastructure --- iter-144 disposition).} This is the committed Mathlib build-out that unlocks Route A, which in turn discharges the positive-genus arm of the witness existence (\cref{def:positiveGenusWitness}). It is \textbf{mandatory and unconditional for the positive-genus witness \emph{object}}: that object must be a genuine \(g\)-dimensional abelian variety (\(\Pic^0_{C/k}\)), and no other route in this chapter produces it. In particular the critical path here is \emph{independent of the genus-\(0\) route choice} --- the genus-\(0\) arm is decoupled onto the trivial object \(\Spec k\) (\cref{def:genusZeroWitness}) and the characteristic-free rigidity statement \cref{prop:rigidity_genus0_curve_to_AV} of \cref{chap:AbelianVarietyRigidity}, neither of which touches the Picard engine. Route~A is the single highest-cost build-out, since Hilbert/Quot schemes are upstream of much of modern algebraic geometry; but once present, the rest of Route A (identity component, smoothness, properness, universal property --- the last being the Albanese property of \(\Pic^0\), Milne \emph{Abelian Varieties} Proposition~6.1) follows by classical arguments already widely formalised in adjacent settings.
466:    \item[\textbf{(\(\gamma\))}] \emph{The rigidity statement for morphisms from a smooth proper geometrically irreducible genus-\(0\) curve to a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme, over an algebraically closed field \(\bar k\).} The genus-\(0\) arm needs \emph{only} this rigidity \emph{statement}, \textbf{decoupled} from both the cotangent-vanishing pile and the Picard representability of (\(\alpha\)): its witness object is the trivial \(\Spec k\), and the statement is the project's named, characteristic-free declaration \cref{prop:rigidity_genus0_curve_to_AV} (\cref{chap:AbelianVarietyRigidity}), carrying \([\mathtt{IsAlgClosed}\ \bar k]\) and \emph{no} \([\mathtt{CharZero}]\) hypothesis (the older \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} of \cref{chap:RigidityKbar}, still carrying both \([\mathtt{IsAlgClosed}\ \bar k]\) and \([\mathtt{CharZero}\ \bar k]\), is the retained fallback-(a) artifact). The \textbf{committed} proof route is the characteristic-free Milne \S I.3 rigidity chain (cube-free) of \cref{chap:AbelianVarietyRigidity} (route~(c): headline \cref{prop:morphism_P1_to_AV_constant}, Milne Proposition~3.10 specialised to \(\mathbb P^1\)), which uses neither the theorem of the cube, nor Serre duality, nor representability. The differential decomposition into the shared cotangent-vanishing pile pieces (i)+(ii)+(iii) of \cref{sec:RigidityKbar_shared_pile} --- cotangent triviality of a group scheme over \(\bar k\) via the functorial shear iso; scheme-level \(\mathrm d f = 0 \Rightarrow\) \(f\) factors through \(\Spec \bar k\) via the \texttt{Differential.ContainConstants} typeclass; characteristic-\(p\) handling via the intrinsic absolute Frobenius \(F_X\) --- is the \textbf{fallback} route~(a), off the critical path but retained in the tree. The genus-\(0\) arm of the witness existence is packaged as \cref{def:genusZeroWitness} (\texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.genusZeroWitness}), which over a general base field \(k\) \emph{descends} the over-\(\bar k\) rigidity conclusion to \(k\): for each \(k\)-rational marked point \(P \in C(k)\) it base-changes the data \((C, A, f, P)\) along \(\Spec \bar k \to \Spec k\) (genus is stable under base change for a geometrically irreducible curve, so \(C_{\bar k}\) is again a genus-\(0\) curve), applies \cref{prop:rigidity_genus0_curve_to_AV} over \(\bar k\) to conclude \(f_{\bar k}\) is constant, then descends the morphism equality back to \(k\) along the faithfully-flat surjection \(\Spec \bar k \to \Spec k\) (Sub-step~C.2.f, whose closing move is \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Flat.epi\_of\_flat\_of\_surjective}). The \(C(k) = \emptyset\) branch is vacuously true (Brauer--Severi conics over \(\mathbb Q\)). Independently of (\(\alpha\)), establishing (\(\gamma\)) together with the descent step (C.2.f --- a multi-iteration base-change sub-build, not a \(\sim 2\)-line step; see the re-costing there) lets the genus-\(0\) part of the witness be discharged unconditionally via \cref{def:genusZeroWitness}; the higher-genus part is packaged as \cref{def:positiveGenusWitness} (\texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.positiveGenusWitness}, iter-134 scaffold) whose body closure is gated on Route A (\(\alpha\)). Per the iter-135 body restructure of \cref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}, the witness existence is now a case-split \(\mathtt{by\_cases}\ h : \genus\,C = 0\) delegating to \cref{def:genusZeroWitness} and \cref{def:positiveGenusWitness} respectively, converting the formerly inline \texttt{sorry} into honest delegation to the two named scaffolds.
467:    \item[\textbf{(\(\beta\), historical only --- not pursued).}] \emph{Symmetric powers of schemes plus finite-group-scheme quotients plus Stein factorisation for proper morphisms.} Documented as a historical alternative not pursued by the project (Route B above); see \cref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} Route B for context. This entry is retained for scholarly continuity only; under the iter-144 disposition, (\(\beta\)) is \emph{not} a build-out the project is gating any of its deliverables on, and (\(\beta\)) does not appear on any active critical path.
470:  \paragraph{Iter-135 body restructure.} The Lean body of \cref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} is, per iter-135 refactor, a case-split \(\mathtt{by\_cases}\ h : \genus\,C = 0\) delegating to \cref{def:genusZeroWitness} (genus-\(0\) arm, \texttt{sorry} body closing iter-151+ under the iter-144 chart-algebra pivot --- see \cref{def:genusZeroWitness} body closure status, revised iter-145) and \cref{def:positiveGenusWitness} (positive-genus arm, \texttt{sorry} body closing M3 --- M3 is committed to Route A per the iter-144 disposition in STRATEGY.md \S~M3; sits behind M2 critical-path during the M2 wait window). The restructure converts the inline \texttt{sorry} on the witness-existence theorem itself into honest delegation to two named scaffolds; the witness existence is therefore conditionally established whenever both arms' bodies close (no Mathlib gap directly on the witness-existence theorem itself, only on each arm).

